node.text: Home is a work in progress. Every day, in ways large and small, we create a space that tells our story – from nurturing creative potential to reconnecting with family to just unplugging from the world outside our walls. We asked some of our customers what they value most in "home." Here are their stories. What does home mean to you?

node.title: What Comes First in Your Home?

node.text: Industrial designer Don Chadwick has developed some of the best chairs on the market – including the iconic 1994 Aeron Chair, co-designed with Bill Stumpf. Chadwick calls his hands-on studio in Santa Monica an “experimental lab,” one that contains the workman’s apparatuses of saws, grinders, lathes, drill presses and vises – along with gallery-worthy modern art, a collection of miniature chairs and good old-fashioned Bondo putty. DWR’s Michael Sainato visited Chadwick in his art-filled studio to talk innovation, happy accidents and the remastered 2016 Aeron Chair.

node.text: Abraham Moradzadeh opened his first rug gallery in Iran as a teenager, traveling the world to source rugs and textiles. He reopened Abraham Rug Gallery in 1980 in Los Angeles, and 25 years later his son Sam joined the company with a plan to expand and modernize beyond antique and vintage rugs to include pieces by contemporary designers and manufacturers. Now headquartered in the West Hollywood Design District, Woven creates its own contemporary designs while continuing to offer vintage and antique rugs, many still sourced by Abraham himself. DWR’s Michael Sainato talked with Woven’s Abraham, Sam and Ben Moradzadeh, along with Design Director Christina Tullock, about the art, culture and emotional connection behind Woven rugs.

node.text: On a beautiful summer evening, we partnered with @mpnewyork's @missyarobbins and @seanbfeeney to celebrate the #ArtOfHosting in grand Italian tradition. Visit our Story and find out how to elevate your own outdoor dinner with their secrets to summer hosting.
